	Nice to be away from the crowds and gambling	FS was having quite a few specials for their most basic room so we decided to try something different on this trip to Vegas. Got a rate of about $330 a night including tax. FS is by far my new favorite in Vegas until the Mandarin opens and I check that out. If you are looking for a place that is away from the gambling sounds and crowds, then this is the perfect place. For a basic room, our room was spacious and had quite a large bathroom. Bed was extra comfy and we had a view of the Mandalay pool area. The FS pool area was exceptional. Pool staff walked around giving out fresh fruit, lemonade, and doing sunglass cleaning and evian spritz. Had a great lunch poolside, highly recommend the grilled cheese sandwhich with tomatoe soup. The only odd thing was that the pool did not have a drink menu, the waitress just said, ask me what you want and I'll see if we can make it. It would be nice if they had some special drinks or at least listed some basics in a drink menu. Brunch in the restaurant was not bad at $35 pp, especially if you are hungover from the night before and just want something close by. Spa and gym facilities were excellent as well. There are attendants in the gym handing out towels, water, and gatorade. Hotel guests can use the steam room in the spa even if they are not having spa treatments. Service all around was the usual FS polished treatment that guests are used to no matter what FS they stay at. The only negative I think of is that it is at the end of the strip, attached to mandalay bay so it is kind of a hike to get to the middle of the strip for shows and dinner. This didn't bother us as we wanted to stay a little further away, but it might be an issue for others.	
	Simply the best!	We have just returned from an eight night stay at The Four Seasons. We were celebrating our anniversary. We could not have made a better choice of hotel. We were upgraded to a Premier View Strip Suite in advance which was simply stunning - views, amenities and acres of space. A celebration cake and a selection of fresh fruit were awaiting us in the room on our first night which was thoughful and much appreciated. Thoughfulness seems to sum up this hotel. The staff are there if you need them but never intrusive - you are made to feel safe from the outset. Several times during our stay messages were left on the answer machine from the on-duty manager just checking if everything was going well and if anything was needed.We ate in Charlie Palmers, the in-house steak restaurant on one night. It was quite expensive - the wine list in particular is eye-wateringly so, and although the food was good the experience was marred to a considerable extent by the noise coming from a nearby table. We had expected a quiet intimate dinner but...Not the hotel's fault but disappointing nonetheless.Although at the extreme south-end of the Strip there is a free tram which runs between Mandalay Bay and Excalibur. Getting around is easy. We booked to see three shows when we were in town and had no problem travelling about. The monorail is a frequent, fast way to travel to most of the points of interest.We bought an item which only after buying realised we would not be able to take back as cabin luggage. It was expensive and we were not keen to put it in the aircraft hold. A quick word with the Concierge staff and it was arranged through their in-house business department for the package to be posted home to the UK - do you prefer UPS or FedEx I was asked. Marvellous!We have stayed in a couple of the rival hotels before this visit - Bellagio and the Venetian to name two but neither come close to The Four Seasons. If you fancy a treat go for it - you won't regret it. I have read reviews here where people have complained about the noise from McCarran Airport. Our room overlooked the airport and the noise didn't bother us at all - in fact is was interesting to sit by the huge floor to ceiling windows with a glass of wine in one hand and just watch the world rolling along.We'll be back!	
