Nov 15 2009 	The New Las Vegas Experience	Took a &quot;staycation&quot; at this super hotel. Perhaps the $145 rate pre-judges my opinion, which is excellent. The property is offering very low rates to Nevada residents - and you must prove that you live in the state, otherwise you are going in at $200 a night plus. Service, service, service is by far the best in any hotel in Las Vegas. Front Desk staff beyond courteous - they are amazing. Over 33 years living in Vegas I've stayed at many hotels. Four Seasons sits atop the Mandalay Bay, but has it's own entrance, lobby, restuarant, spa and pools. Unless you have a strip view - you'd never know you were in &quot;Sin City.&quot; Room is comfortable; bathroom with 'soaking tub' wonderful. Quiet. Elevators go from lobby and bypass every floor until 35 or 36, which is nice. AND, they offer smoking rooms, which I know is very rare in a Four Seasons hotel - perhaps it is still permitted in Las Vegas, except in restuarants. I look forward to my next &quot;staycation&quot; at this great hotel.	
Nov 15 2009 	On oasis of calm after the full-on Vegas strip.	As a traveller who usually stays in budget hotels this was a bit of a treat for me. I had the opportunity to stay in this wonderful hotel and I do not use the term lightly. I have to admit that I do not get the opportunity to stay in 5+ star hotels on a regular basis so my review will be based on my limited experience of them.The hotel itself is located at the top of the Mandalay Bay complex located on floor 35-39. It has it's own independant lobby and elevators at ground level, so you do not need to walk through any casinos to get to the hotel. From the beginning we were welcomed. On our arrival from the airport we were checked in swiftly and courteously then shown where the elevators were. We got given cold bottled water to refresh us after our journey. The elevator goes to the floors 35-39 and you have access to the casino level if you wish.Our room was on the 39th floor with a strip view. The room was a twin room with two very comfortable queen sized beds. It was well very clean and well decorated with solid wood furniture and soft furnishings. There was a large screen television with access to many channels, movies, games and the Internet. The bedside table had a lamp, ipod dock and bedside alarm clock. There was a large comfortable chair and footstool to relax as well as a desk and two chairs with writing equipment. There was a well-stocked minibar with snacks and drinks and plenty of closet space. The bathroom was clean and bright with a marble suite and a great shower and bath. Plenty of clean towels and bathroom products like L'Occitane soap and shampoo.Our room service was super-efficient and we often returned to find our beds had been made and the room had been cleaned. Fresh fruit was delivered on one of the nights as well as bottled water on a regular basis. There were lots of other services that we had access to that we didn't necessarily use like laundry services, in-room dining and use of the business and conference centres. My colleague did visit the spa which is at the ground level and he was full of praise about it.The hotel has got a steak house as well as a contemporary Italian restaurant called Verandah. I'll write a seperate review about that.I would definately recommend this hotel to anyone who has the opportunity to stay at it. It was an oasis of calm after the full-on sights and sounds of the Vegas strip.	
