Sep 7 2009 	A Great Trip to Las Vegas	Finally...a place to stay in Las Vegas where you can relax in an entirely peaceful environment yet be just a door away from the typical hubbub and activities of a higher-end casino, and only a short drive from the main part of the Strip.My husband and I were at the Four Seasons 4 nights over Labor Day weekend. Arrived Thursday night and had a very relaxing light (late) dinner at Verandah with excellent food and service. Spent our days at the pool with excellent pool service (not sure what the staff to guest ratio was but it was high enough that we felt really well looked-after.) When we first arrived and chose our lounge chairs we received a full pitcher of ice water that was refilled throughout the day along with nice treats throughout the day (popsicle, bit of frozen banana, iced towel - scented with eucalyptus on one of the days, evian water spritz, frozen melon ball) which were really nice. The pool service was very attentive and genuinely friendly. The pool area is not huge as in some of the other Strip hotels but it was completely adequate for the number of guests. Some lounge chairs had all-day sun exposure whereas others had all-day shade and some had partial sun/partial shade depending on time of day (which can be a good thing in Las Vegas in the summer!) Rooms were very nice and very clean. Bed was very comfy (not too soft and not too firm!) Twice-daily housekeeping service was really nice. The FS has two restaurants: Verandah for breakfast, lunch, dinner (all excellent) and Charlie Palmer for dinner - really wonderful food and especially wonderful service.Logistically, the Four Seasons occupies the top 5 floors of the Mandalay Bay Hotel. Its ground level facilities (lobby, restaurants, pool, spa, exercise room, etc) are completely separate from the MB. The elevator takes you from the lobby straight to the 35th-39th floors. If you were to never take the small side door on the &quot;C&quot; level (for casino) into the MB you'd never know you were next door. Being separate from the MB allows the FS to remain completely without a bit of cigarette smoke in case that is important to you.If you DO go into the MB you will find that you can easily walk to the Luxor (without having to go outside into the outdoor weather) and thereby be almost to hotels such as Excalibur, MGM Grand and New York...so the rest of the Strip is not far. If you want to go much farther than MGM Grand/New York New York take a cab and make sure the driver takes the freeway 1 or 2 exits north (depending where you are going) rather than Las Vegas Blvd because the traffic can be a giant mess. Cab fare to the central strip area (Wynn, Mirage, Venetian) was about $15.00-$16.00 without tip.Speaking of tips: make sure you tip for good service! I always say &quot;feel good about your tips&quot; and that means if someone has done something to make your life easier or more pleasant...return the favor! I see waaay too many people forgetting to tip...especially if you are going to stay somewhere as nice as the Four Seasons...tip it up! The doorman, the person checking you in, the bag attendant delivering your bags, the pool attendant setting up your chaise lounge, the housekeeper...don't forget! (Especially you young ones...get in the habit!) (Sorry to be preachy...)So, in all, if you like Las Vegas for the fun options but would prefer a calm and quiet place to stay (especially if the noise of Las Vegas gets to you...) stay at the Four Seasons. You can have your fun and return to the &quot;oasis of serenity&quot; just by passing through the door. Have a great time! We did!	
Sep 7 2009 	Disappointed	The Four Seasons Las Vegas was supposed to be a nice treat for us during our recent trip to Las Vegas. We were disappointed. I have stayed in most of the hotels on the strip, and recently in both Mandalay Bay and THE Hotel. I would recommend staying in either of these hotels over the Four Seasons.The Four Seasons rooms are very much like any regular Mandalay Bay rooms. The lobby was nice, but way too far from the rest of the Mandalay. Valet parking was $18. How does every other hotel have free valet and Four Seasons requires you to pay for it, that makes no sense to me. I parked at Mandalay because I never saw a point to paying that fee.The alure of the Four Seasons is the service. However, I found their service to be lacking. The front desk nicely offered to walk us to the elevator which honestly turned into a elaborate sales pitch for the spa. He never even told us where anything else was. On the walk between the front desk he told me all I needed to know about the spa, but not how to get to the pool, fitness, or even the elevator. In fact, when he left us in front of the spa I had to ask him how to get to the elevators from there. He also asked which paper we would like, none was ever delivered.The true test of our trip came on Saturday night. My wife with 30 minutes left before meeting friends for a show panicked because the hair dryer in our room was not working. I thought, not a problem, a hotel known for service should have a new hair dryer here in less than 5 minutes. I called and told them the problem and I needed a hair dryer in a hurry. Saving you the long story 30 minutes, 4 phone calls, and 1 trip to the front desk later we left.....and just as we were walking out the new hair dryer finally shows up. Was this a big deal? Not really, but if you are going to run an upper end property this is a simple guest request, they failed!In summary, most reviews rave about the Four Seasons. It is nice, but I would recommend going eslewhere....we certainly will.	
