Aug 11 2009 	Great stay at The Four Seasons Las Vegas	Just returned from a great trip visiting the West and had the pleasure of staying at The Four Seasons in Las Vegas. I can take Vegas for only a few days (too much noise, too many crowds). The beauty of The Four Seasons is that it's tucked away inside the Mandalay Bay and you escape all the noise, people and goings-on there. (The Mandalay Bay lobby was always crowded no matter what time we walked through.) As soon as you enter The Four Seasons, it's very quiet and tranquil. We stayed in a one-bedroom suite on the 35th floor. Loved it! We had an abundance of room for 3 people. (Really, the suite was huge!) We need to be able to spread out and had plenty of room to do so. Housekeeping provided great service and they were always leaving bottles of water. (I guess they don't want you to dehydrate in the Vegas sun!) There was also a candy dish on the coffee table that kept getting refilled, to my son's delight!Guests of The Four Seasons also have access to the Mandalay Bay's pool/wave pool/beach area, which my ten-year-old son was anxious to try. We walked over during our first afteroon and was shocked to see how crowded it was. (I thought people avoided Vegas in the heat of the summer!) There was nowhere to sit, so we thought about renting a cabana for the afternoon as there were plenty which sat empty. I'm sorry, but at $400, there was no way that was going to happen! Absolutely crazy! (It's the Mandalay Bay, for Pete's sake!) We thought about trying the lazy river before heading back, but you have to purchase an inner tube for almost $50!! We were happy to head back to the pool at The Four Seasons. They know how to treat their guests. The staff immediately came over to us with towels, set up our chairs and brought us a pitcher of ice water. Throughout the afternoon, they offered us complimentary Evian mists, popsicles, frozen melon, and chilled towels. No one provides service like The Four Seasons.We had dinner and breakfast at The Four Seasons' Verandah restaurant. We had dinner our first night and were exhausted, so we wanted to eat quickly and go to sleep. I ordered the short ribs which sounded so good. Unfortunately, when my meal arrived, it was cold. Not even lukewarm, but cold. On the plus side, the few bites I had were delicious, but I wasn't going to eat a cold meal. They, of course, offered to make a fresh plate for me, but I was just too tired to eat, so they removed it from the bill. We also had breakfast there which was alright, but nothing great. I recommend eating elsewhere as there are so many great restaurants in Vegas.We did ask the concierge for restaurant recommendations as we were meeting up with family near Caesar's and wanted to find a restaurant to suit everyone's tastes . The concierge recommended Spago in the Forum Shops at Caesar's. It was excellent! Everyone enjoyed their meals and I was very impressed with their food and service!When we return to Vegas, we will definitely stay at The Four Seasons again. Top notch!	
Aug 8 2009 	Exemplary Service	We are typically in value-priced (meaning under $100) hotels when in Las Vegas - primarily because we spend such little of our time in the room. But this time, we decided to check out the number one rated hotel in Las Vegas (according to tripadvisor and many other critics/reviews). We were not disappointed. From the moment we arrived until check-out, we were pampered and treated like VIP's. I have to commend the pool and valet managers for excellent staff and extraordinary service. In addition, guests at the Four Seasons have access to all of the amenities of the Mandalay Bay property, and that makes this the ideal get-away. The Four Seasons has a subdued elegance, not like the Bellagio that just screams opulence. It is quiet and private and maintains a sense of civility amidst the chaos of the Strip. From the private entrance to the seldom crowded elevators to the non-smoking, non-gambling atmosphere - this is not the Vegas that we had come to know in years past. Nonetheless, pushing the &quot;C&quot; button in the elevators takes you to the lobby of the Mandalay Bay where the action (if you're looking for it) is waiting for you. Even the maintenance staff (e.g., the guys in overalls fixing ceiling panels) were courteous, friendly and ever-ready with a smile and a &quot;hello, how are you today.&quot; That is over-the-top service, and it sets this hotel apart from not only those in Las Vegas, but 5-star hotels from around the world. If I could, I would give it 6 stars.We will definitely be back.	
