Jul 22 2008 	A sanctuary in the midst of chaos	This is our third stay at this property and we would not go to Vegas unless we were able to stay at the Four Seasons. As soon as you walk through the front door, you forget that you are in Vegas. The entire staff is super accomodating and extremely well trained. There are no lines to contend with for check in, taxi service, etc. like at the other hotels on the strip.The spa facilities are spotless, the staff is professional and the treatments were sublime. I had the raindrop masage and a facial. I left the spa feeling like I had been on vacation for a month. It was my friend's birthday and she left with a &quot;birthday&quot; bag of samples and full size products from the spa staff.All dinner and show arrangements were handled prior to our arrival by the concierge. The tickets they got us for Beatles Love were first row center. The seats (and show) were fantastic. The one glitch was the Sunday breakfast buffet. Similar to an experience we had three years ago, the hot items on the buffet were room temperature. Our friend however, gave his plate to one of the waiters who promptly brought it back to the microwave and heated it for him. The food is first rate when it is hot! The pool area is slightly crowded, but you can always find a chair. The staff is always around offering to clean your sunglasses, spritz you with Evian, bring drinks/lunch and offer free creamsicles which are nice when it is 107 degrees! There are also misters around the entire pool area to help keep you cool. One negative is that you can hear the booming music from the Mandalay Bay pools, but that cannot be avoided since they are situated so closely.This was another great experience with the Four Seasons which never fails to disappoint.	
Jul 21 2008 	Utopia Las Vegas	Our stay at the Four Seasons Hotel Las Vegas commenced on July 1 through July 8, 2008, and encompassed the July 4th holiday weekend. As with our past Utopian stays here, our latest visit was no exception, and as such, is the reason we choose to stay here year after year. The criteria I cite as providing an A+ hotel experience are as follows: the quality, ambience and cleanliness of the property, the accommodating and friendly, personable staff, as well as the not-to-be underestimated excellent location, ease of access and proximity to the greater Las Vegas area and airport. As a forty-something, male, experienced traveler, I offer you my perspectives:This hotel is unequivocally the freshest, finest smelling hotel in Las Vegas, with the earthtone marble entry foyer and corridors immaculately buffed and polished, and the carpeted upper floor corridors in new and superior condition. I would best describe the decor and furnishings within the hotel as refined and traditional with contemporary and Far East accents, replete with fresh floral arrangements and greenery, which only serves to compliment the airy, tranquil, spacious and quiet ambience one encounters upon entering the hotel, which in my opinion, is perhaps it's most sought after attribute. It is a very dignified atmosphere, and due to it's well crafted sophistication and eclectic appointments, it is very comfortable, yet not &quot;over the top.&quot; And even in light of the fact that the hotel was full over the July 4th holiday weekend, it never once felt crowded.Our check-in was smooth and efficient and within minutes we were on our way to one of the (3) express elevators to the 35th-39th Four Seasons floors. Our room was a Deluxe category (560 sq. ft.), amply spacious with earthen-tones decor, 39th floor, North Wing location with a sunset view west overlooking the Spring Mountains/Red Rock/Mt. Charleston panorama. Our flight was a late arrival and therefore turndown service had already been performed upon our room, complete with a rolled praline and dark chocolate ganache welcome presentation. Turndown service at this hotel consists of dimming the lights, drawing the draperies, placement of white linen bedside mats and white terrycloth slippers, fresh bedside bottles of water with inverted glass, tuning the large flatscreen plasma TV to the Four Seasons channel which shows Zen-like ambient naturescapes accompanied by ambient, contemporary jazz and classical music, as well as fresh towel, white terrycloth robe and amenity replenishment. Twice per day housekeeping is definitely a fine point of this hotel. The large marble bathroom with soaking tub (her favorite) and glass enclosed marble shower (my favorite) is more than ample and spacious, with a separate enclosed commode. The bathroom was amply stocked with citrus-accented L'Occitane amenities, hair dryer, bath towels and the signature Four Seasons white terrycloth robe and slippers. The room itself is also stocked with a refrigerated mini-bar, a Cuisinart coffee maker and an iron &amp; ironing board. I must also note that this room, furniture included, was immaculately clean, fresh and not worn, and every attention to detail was taken by our housekeeper, from the folded points on the toilet tissue and tissue box, to the tightly and smoothly made bed, pillows and down duvet. As well, as robes, towels, and bedding are white here, they were just that....immaculately clean, white and fresh smelling.Upon entering the pool area, the sweet aroma of eucalyptus greets one at the door. The pool area itself, replete with a pool bar, top screened pergolas, palm trees and an ample supply of misters, affords one the option of privacy or publicity, sun or shade, depending on where one chooses to locate. I personally prefer the pool's laid back atmosphere (although not to be read boring, just more relaxed) to that of the more &quot;manic&quot; pool areas of corresponding resort hotels. I found the pool staff providing set-ups and service to be very polite, friendly and accommodating, yet never intrusive. A very enjoyable and pleasant pool experience. As well, I find the adjoining Mandalay Bay casino (conveniently just steps away through &quot;the tranquility door&quot;) and restaurants (a plethura of eclectic epicurian alternatives to the higher end Charlie Palmer's Steak House and The Verandah at the Four Seasons, albeit not entirely inexpensive) a definite asset to this hotel as well (although being a vegetarian, it does pose certain dining challenges, though not insurmountable). The casino itself is tastefully adorned in off-white and gold appointments and is not claustrophobic, is comfortably yet not overly lighted, seems to have clearer air than most, as well as possessing a worthy array of entertainment choices and venues. And in my opinion, this casino provides the perfect venue to &quot;see and be seen&quot;, after all, nothing trumps Saturday night in Las Vegas.....you will feel distinguished here.The staff at the Four Seasons Las Vegas were extremely conscientious, accommodating and polite, and of particular note, very friendly and personable. From the very capable and efficient reservations agents, front desk staff, housekeeping and door/bellmen, one need not fear class intimidation here, as the professionalism and genuineness of the staff make this hotel a very welcoming atmosphere. This is not a boutique hotel, nor is it one of the more inexpensive hotels in Las Vegas, but as a hotel with only 424 rooms, it offers unsurpassed personalized service and quality. My only caveat here is that while other luxury hotels may offer more &quot;real estate&quot; for the price regarding room value, when viewed objectively and compositely, location, ease of access, quality, service, (and what I perceive to be) a comfortable staff to guest ratio and a smaller, more manageable property serve make this hotel a premium cost/benefit value.And finally, location....This hotel is superiorly located at the South end of the Strip (interpreted as construction zone and tower crane free) atop the Mandalay Bay Hotel, offers valet or self-park options, and offers extremely unencumbered ease of access via Frank Sinatra Drive and Las Vegas Blvd. to Interstate 15 (points north and south) and Interstate 215 (points east: Green Valley, Lake Las Vegas and Lake Mead, and west: Summerlin and Red Rock Canyon), all within 30 minutes travel time, as well as being 10 minutes from the airport. Regarding the aforementioned locations: so many restaurants, so little time....That being said, staying at the Four Seasons Hotel Las Vegas is definitively worth the price of admission....and watching the sun set over Mt. Charleston....priceless....peace....	
Jul 11 2008 	Exceeded My Expectations-Awesome!!!!	Just got back from a Vegas 4th of July holiday /anniversary celebration weekend. Stayed 4 nights at the Four Seasons. This was our 1st trip to Vegas, and what a fantastic trip. After reading numerous reviews about the Bellagio, Wynn, Venetian, Ceasars Palace, Mandalay Bay, and the Four Seasons...we decided to take a gamble before gambling in Vegas, and chose to stay at the Four Seasons. It was fantastic!!!! Great excitement, fun, and plenty of action, and just enough quite R &amp; R to balance out our 4 night stay. Having access to the Mandalay casino, pools, restaurants, etc was non-eventful because everything is literally right there together and really all located within Mandalay Bay. The room was beyond awesome, and definitely offered the peace and quiet we were looking for, whenever we choose to retreat back to the room. We have already decided that our next trip to Vegas, will be complete by returning to the Four Seasons!!!	
Jul 10 2008 	The quietest in Vegas....	I'm not going to lie. I gave this property five stars because, well, its an excellent hotel. But would I stay here again? I don't know.  The truth is, The Four Seasons in Vegas is great if you are looking for a little down time. You can go spend your entire night in the casino at Mandelay Bay and then step into the FS elevator and its instantly quiet. But is that a good thing? It is Vegas, after all.It worked out well for us because I was staying with my family, that tends to be a little quieter and hates noise at night. However, if you are here for outrageous Vegas-themed suites, late night parties, etc., this place is NOT for you. Aditionally, since this place does not have a casino it is VERY expensive. You could book a much larger suite in another Vegas hotel for nearly half of the price. Then again, you would not be guaranteed this quiet. So it's really up to you when traveling in Vegas what kind of atmosphere you are looking for. By the way, pool is very nice. Pool attendants were very nice, and I was the only one in the pool. Very relaxing. Also you may want to be aware Mandaley Bay/FS is at the very beginning of the Strip, so you will have to walk (don't even try to drive/take a cab...it will take hours) a pretty decent distance to get anywhere.	
Jul 9 2008 	Best Hotel on the Vegas Strip!	Last year was our first trip to Vegas and spent two days of Hell in the adjoining &quot;THE Hotel&quot; in Mandalay bay. We checked out and made the long trek to the Four Seasons (Note; If possible, use the private entrance on the other side instead of walking all the way through the Mandalay Bay. However, be aware that there are no sidewalks around the entry way).I'll be completely honest in saying this: Walking into the Four Seasons was like walking into paradise. The quiet, the beautiful ambiance, the smells. There are no casinos, people greet you at the front door and they quickly learn your name. If you have to stand in line at the front desk, the service is quick and efficient. Being that Vegas is hot, there is always bottled water available. Sometimes the doormen/valet will give you some after they bring your car to you, or call you a cab. Talk about service!The hotel set up is a little strange; The lobby and so forth are on the ground level, and there is another level that will take you to the door that leads to the Mandalay Bay Casino (for those who want to have easy access). The room floors don't start until floor 38 or so, and the main floor elevators have a side door that leads to the Four Seasons private pool. Inside, is just gorgeous; marble hallways, subtle beige tones; it's like walking into a mansion.Rooms are large and comfortable and my favorite part about staying at the Four Seasons is that they have Turner Classic Movies! Hopefully if you are a classic movie fan (who finds this info useful!), they will still offer this station! The bathrooms aren't huge, but they are spacious, with tubs, a fairly good-sized shower, robes, a vanity section with a magnifying mirror and double doors to the bathroom for total privacy; as well as a separate commode area. The last time we stayed here, we were given (without asking) a room with an incredible view of the strip. Just amazing. I could have stared out the window for hours! The pool is wonderful and I have learned from other reviews that there are special amenities available, which I will definitely inquire about. The nice thing is that the employees will find you some chairs, drape the towels over them for you, and generally give you whatever you need. The only thing I don't like about the pool is that (like Mandalay Bay), it closes at 7pm. However, the spa is open until 9pm and it deserves it's own paragraph!The spa use at the Four Seasons is FREE (except for of course, treatments and massages, etc), if you can believe it. Something Free in Vegas! Last time we took advantage of it after a long day sightseeing at Hoover Dam. The pool had already closed, but we took a change of clothes and went down to the spa where we took showers in the huge individual shower rooms. The showers have amenities like shampoo, soap, conditioner, you can get razors, feminine products, q-tips, cotton balls, moisturizer... almost anything you can think of. It's here. There is an area that has vanity mirrors where you can sit down (in the plush robe that you get when you ask for a locker key-even slippers and a towel!), and they have hair dryers, hair gel, etc. There is even a couples lounge which is wonderful for husbands and wives. Just ask the attendant to show you the way. Once inside, the lights are already dim (to the point that I could have slept for days in there), and very soft music plays in the background. There are magazines available to read, and I must mention the steam room with its eucalyptus steam. Absolutely heavenly! This is the ONLY place I will stay when I am visiting the Las Vegas area and plan on spending time on the strip. Need I say more? It's SO worth the splurge! I should also add: This year, our staying here was contingent on whether or not we would return to Vegas and I think it will continue to be that way.	
