Nov 26 2007 	an oasis in the desert esp. if you're not into gambling	my family and i (with a 2 year old!) stayed at the four seasons in las vegas over thanksgiving weekend. generally, i agree with most of the reviews of the hotel, but wanted to highlight the following:1. the service is truly superior, esp. for las vegas. very consistent with four seasons globally. no request was too small, and everyone, from the front desk to the concierge to bellmen to car drivers to the restaurant staff, was friendly and efficient.2. we loved the intimate setting. you will NOT feel like cattle (like you do at most large casino resorts in vegas / restaurants / the airport, spas etc.)3. we loved the fact there was no casino (none of us are major gamblers). no smoke-filled lobbies, clanging slot machines, etc. however, access to mandalay bay's casino is fast and easy through the four seasons elevators.4. the hotel is incredibly kid friendly, and caters to them. our 2 year old had a great time, and the staff was very kind to him. milk &amp; cookies on arrival, little stuffed animal gifts, great patience in the restaurant, really good kids menus, etc.5. the spa was first rate, and not too crowded. the waiting area had about 10 seats, compared to more than 50 women in robes and slippers waiting around at canyon ranch at the venetian (where we stayed last time).6. the verandah was probably one of the best four seasons hotel restaurants we've ever encountered (and we've been to a lot of them!) truly great food (not haute cuisine, but just simple, well executed dishes) and fine service. the sunday brunch was memorable (they actually make small portions of everything so you can sample!)this is NOT the hotel you want if you're looking to party / shop / gamble in the heart of the strip (i'd stay at the venetian or bellagio for that). cab rides there were about $15 each way and a pain in the neck. but for us, the four seasons was as close to perfect as possible in las vegas.	
