Sep 6 2007 	Best for non-Gamblers Romantic Luxury	A bit of a secret, the Four Seasons rooms are at the top of Mandalay Bay, but are all Four Seasons with the usual over the top service and amenities. If you don't want to walk through a casino to navigate your hotel, this is the place for you. A traditional 5 star hotel lobby (no slots, no smoking, etc), a soothing, quiet, luxurious ambiance. The staff are not just eager to serve, but make you feel like you are the only one in the place. Rooms are top notch -- 42 in plasma with DVD, VCR. Huge bathrooms with soaking tubs, fluffy robes, massive towels, spa toiletries. Fabulous beds with down pillows and comforters. Floor to ceiling windows with views of the mountains or the Strip (since the 4S is at the extreme south end, you get a great view!). In room coffee, tea, fridge and apples at the front and spa desk everyday. Complimentary bottled water. My favorite touch was a dimmer switch on every lamp. I could read at night without bothering my spouse or we could dim the lights to watch a movie. Top notch spa on site. The pool is not huge, but has two whirlpools and is attached via a card access gate to the 11+ acres of Mandalay Bay's &quot;water park&quot; like pool area. Teens would LOVE it. So, you get the best of both worlds. Slip on your suit, meet the pool staff at the entrance to the pool and they will set up the chaise of your choice (shade or no?) with a cushy terry chair cover, give you a huge fluffy towel and bring you a pitcher of ice water. Need a spritz of Evian over you to keep cool? Cucumber slices for your eyes? No problem, and on the house. Poolside bar and food service available and not at bad prices either. A delicious fruit smoothie was $8 and large grilled chicken salad $15. When you tire of the calm classic music and the pampering, just take your 4S card key with you and go down the path to the adjacent Mandalay Bay pool complex where rock music blares and you have access to lazy river, wave pool, sandy beach, etc. Bring your blow-up tube from home to avoid the $20 per day charge for renting tubes and you're all set. Need some choices for eating out, again, you've got the best steakhouse in Vegas in the Charlie Palmer right there at the Four Seasons or a raft of restaurants in the adjacent M. Bay hotel. If you want gambling, that's there too. But, back in the Four Seasons cocoon, you can forget about the smoking, loud, bright side of Vegas...until you're ready for the night on town. And then, you can hop a cab, or from the Mandalay Bay, take the free tram as far as the Excalibur. Then, you are in the heart of the south strip with lots in an easy walk. My only wish was that they would keep the pool open after dark. We didn’t have our kids this time, but they had lots of accommodations for little people.	
Sep 3 2007 	World Class Hotel	I booked this hotel based on comments from Trip Advisor and it was perfect and just as people described. This was part of a round trip in the US and we had no desire to go to Las Vegas but realised it was a good base from which to see the Grand Canyon. My husband and I travelled with our two sons Age 12 and 10 and they loved Vegas. The Four Seasons has the top four floors of the Mandalay Bay hotel, and as a result is very quiet, there is no gambling at the hotel ( which means it is a haven of tranquility ) but has the advantage of having access to the facillities of the Mandalay Bay Hotel - notably the huge swimming pool with the wave machine and Lazy Man's river which the boys adored. The service was excellent from the moment you walked in the door - with water on arrival to counter the 115 degree heat. We were a little early to check in but they let us have one room immediately and phoned us a soon as the other room was ready. The children's bathroom had alphabetical sponges in each of their names, laid out in their bathroom, and on returning to their room in the evenings they were provided with Coca Cola and Popcorn - not quite what you wanted them to have a bed time but a nice touch nevertheless.The concierges were incredible and had every possible information at their finger tips and were able to book shows instantly - I would say the best concierge we have ever experienced. We were only there 2 nights but saw two shows and visited the Grand Canyon by helicpopter ( 30mins drive away for pick up ).Overall it was a great stay with the Four Season making everything perfect in Las Vegas. ( We did not go for the gambling... )	
Sep 2 2007	Okay stay	Let me start of by saying that I've stayed at the MGM, Mirage, Wynn, and Ritz Carlton Vegas. I've read many reviews regarding the FS Vegas location and agree on most comments. Room:The rooms are bland (if not borderline dull and a little outdated). We had a premier strip view delux room. Only 1 sink in the bathroom with separate toliet closet, and nice shower. The room was large with a 46 inch flat screen lcd television. But the furnishing was outdated and the bed wasn't all that comfortable at all. I rate the room B+Room Service:I called down for espresso shot and cappuccino and the room service attendant was rude. He implied that the wait would be long because they were backed up. And said something along the lines of &quot;if you really want coffee, it'll take 25-40 minute&quot;. I asked regarding if they had pasteries with my coffee and what kind and he said &quot;yes but we don't really have time&quot;. This kind of answer is horrible. I rate this a FLocation:Although most people like the fact that it is not a casino resort, that was really one of the turn offs for us. You come all the way to Vegas and then you want to be in a non-casino destination? Well, perhaps you should go somewhere else then. We've stayed at the Ritz Carlton Lake Las Vegas resort and it beats this resort hands down as far as &quot;non casino&quot; resort and the tranquility of it. This resort is not kid friendly either. There is no kiddy pool or services catering kids. I rate the pool -- BPrice:Our price on a Saturday evening for a premier strip view room was $525. Not cheap considering the Wynn had a parlor Suite at $499 during the same time and the Bellagio had a Penthouse suite listed for $599. The FS Vegas resort is by far one of the more expensive hotels in Vegas. I rate the room -- F.Service:Other than the fact that room service stinks, the bellman was nice, valet was efficient and informative, he front desk was professional, and the concierge did what was asked. So A++ for service and professionalism.Overrall:If you desire a non vegas destination while being close enough to gamble, I would recommend the Ritz Carlton Lake Las Vegas or the Westin Vegas resort. For the price, the FS Vegas has not met my expectations.	
Aug 27 2007 	Great FS experience	Just returned from a 6 night stay at FS Vegas. It was our fourth time in the city and were really looking forward to our break, having always been very pleased with other FS properties we have been to. It turned out we were not disappointed. The FS provides the ultimate balance in great service ( so often missing from even the best mega hotels on the Strip ) and easy access to the glitz and glamour that makes a Vegas break. Rooms are typical FS, quietly classy, but its the service that makes it stand out. Every member of staff seemed so attentive , especially at the pool, which is is delightful. The food at Verandah was also very good, although would agree with previous poster that a separate lounge bar would be good, as Verandah closes early. All in all a really great hotel , and having stayed at The Wynn last year ,and Venetian a few years back, the best that Vegas has to offer (although I do believe that first timers should try out the big hotels first , just to make it clear where the differences are ! ). As a travel agent who has been to many 5 star properties around the world this comes highly recommended.	
