Nov 14 2006 	Expensive but worth it.	This hotel is outstanding in every respect, one of the nicest I have stayed in, in 30 years of serious hotel-going. If you don't gamble--and do travel with a pet--the Four Seasons is really the only choice in Las Vegas, in my opinion. (If I couldn't stay there, I wouldn't go to Las Vegas at all.) My husband and I booked a room in September, on the penultimate day of a cross-country trip, an impulse buy after the hellhole that is Rock Springs, Wyoming. Calling from our car, at the very last minute, we got an astonishingly low rate on a lovely room overlooking the Strip. I wouldn't recommend this path to everyone, but having that low, low rate in your file allows you to negotiate a pretty good deal on subsequent trips. Last night, I booked 5 nights in January for the Miss America Pageant (go, Miss Rhode Island!). The rate I got, directly from the Four Seasons for the same lovely room with a view, was lower than the lowest rate for the cheapest room on any travel Website--about halfway between the super-low rate I got in September and the first price quoted when I called.What's so great about this hotel? The staff. Either they deliberately hire exceptionally warm, kind, friendly, and welcoming people, or they put everyone through some intensive--and effective!--hospitality boot camp, who knows which? Whatever they do, it works. Everyone on the staff was wonderful: reservations, parking, bellmen, desk, housekeeping, room service, concierge. (I didn't have time for the pool or spa.) From check-in to check-out, we did not have a single bad encounter. Also (if this matters to you) they really like dogs and do everything possible to pamper them. Even behavior that annoyed me--like a woman who let her pooch off-leash and played ball with him in the elevator lobby (you know who you are, lady with the chihuahua!)--was met with genial amusement by the Four Seasons staff. The giant Samoan security guard was not a charmer, true. But he certainly made me feel secure!We had only one tiny complaint. About an hour before we planned to check out and drive to Santa Barbara, I got the bright idea of ordering a picnic lunch. The Four Seasons does offer delicious-sounding box lunches, but you have to order them 3 hours in advance. Which, for most people, means having the bright idea the night before. (Unfortunately, I am not one of the Organized People.) Room Service would not make an exception, no matter how much I sweet-talked, wheedled, and whined. They said &quot;no&quot; very nicely, but still. This meant my poor, long-suffering husband had to trudge down to the Mandalay Bay to fetch our lunch. Which turned out to be OK, but they gave it to him piled high on one of those ugly cardboard trays, so awkward to carry--particularly with a rambunctious bull terrier! Then again, at check-out, the desk guy whisked the offending tray away and returned a few minutes later with our lunch neatly packed in a lovely box. Now that I know the drill, I'll order our picnic the night before. And I am so looking forward to the serenity of the pool, spa, and cucumber slices after hard nights of pageant-going!	
Nov 9 2006 	An oasis in Las Vegas	We've just returned from a 3 night stay at the Four Seasons which we'd booked as a splurge after 3 weeks touring the South West. We certainly made the right choice. Our room was on the 39th floor with the most amazing view of the Strip. The bed was the most comfortable we'd ever slept on, and everything about the room was so well thought out. Housekeeping service was impeccable - they even put my husband's razor on recharge when it got low. The toiletries (L'Occitane) were fab. We had all the facilities of the Mandalay Bay, but were able to retreat to our little oasis whenever we wanted peace and quiet. The Four Seasons pool is great - you are pampered from the minute you enter the complex, pitchers of iced water, popsicles, melon, sunglasses cleaned etc etc. We walked to the main MBay pool with the wave machine etc, but it just felt like a noisy beach club with booming music and we were glad to go back to our own little 'haven'. It was the little touches that we liked so much - bottles of iced water in your car when the valet returns it and the offer of directions to wherever you are going. And the way they lay out the TV guide and remote control by your bed in the evening. My husband sent his boots to the shoeshine and they were returned by the morning, perfectly shined and individually wrapped in tissue paper!The restaurants are great - you can use all Manadalay Bay's facilities and just charge it to your room.One word of warning tho - if you suffer from vertigo you may want to give it a miss. All the windows are floor to ceiling, from the moment you step out of the lift, to the windows in the rooms. It takes a while to get used to it - particularly when you see the helicopters buzzing below you! 3 nights just wasn't enough!	
Oct 27 2006 	Nice hotel but not exceptional	My wife and I stayed at the Four Seasons for a weekend in October 2006.As background, the Four Seasons Hotel is simply the top floors of the Mandalay Bay Hotel. The Four Seasons has its own ground entrance and elevators -- and no casino (although you can easily go into the one at Mandalay Bay).The hotel was acceptable, pleasant and visually attractive – but not exceptional for the price, particularly with all the options available in Las Vegas. The Superior room was of average size and appointment. Some of the furniture was dinged and bathroom only had a single-basin vanity. The closet and cabinetry were premium and the room had a large plasma TV.The service was good, but not flawless. We ordered room-service breakfast on Saturday morning. It arrived on-time and at the correct temperature. The server has friendly and set up the room efficiently. I ordered a cholesterol-free omelet which was really tasty (it’s hard to do an egg-white omelet worth eating). However, late in the day when we came back from the pool, the plates had not been picked up. We had to call room-service to have someone come and bus the room.The hotel will deliver either the Wall Street Journal or the New York Times. We got our Saturday paper and were looking forward to the Sunday Times, but it never arrived.The Four Seasons has access to its own pool with an older, more sedate crowd than the many pools at the Mandalay. We used the pools at both facilities because the Mandalay Bay has some fun features like a wave pool and the Lazy River with a current.The hotel is pretty far from the core of the Strip at the end of the airport. It can take a while to get a cab from the hotel simply because it doesn’t have the same in-and-out traffic of the other resorts.	
