Aug 20 2006	Four reasons to enjoy the Four Seasons - late July 2006	If you need to ease your way into a very different time zone or just make that transition to Las Vegas living, then there are four very good reasons to choose the Four Seasons. It just fell short of 5 TripAdvisior 'O's - the whys and wherefores in a moment. The fab-four facts are i) Good rooms, ii) Cool pool, iii) Super service and iv) Casino-free but easy to use Mandalay Bay one if you feel the urge.It was our second stay here as a family of five (three children aged from 10 to 16) and we arrived after a 10 hour flight from the UK. We'd booked two connecting rooms, with a good discount off the second room, a $50 per day voucher for extras (about two breakfasts) and entry to the Shark Reef at Mandalay Bay.At check-in we were pleased to find only one person in front of us and that we'd been upgraded to a Strip-view room. The rooms are huge with great views, even if the view of the Strip is only a fifth of the view as a whole (only mention it because if I'd paid for a Strip view I'd been disappointed it didn't fill the panorama).We'd have been happy having a twin-bedded room with a roll-away bed for the smallest child and saved ourselves $250 a night on the second discounted room, but the hotel was unwilling to budge on this one. I'd been told it was for fire safety reasons when I'd made the call to book the rooms - but we found lots of other hotels happy to oblige in San Diego, Santa Barbara and Venice Beach (one of the reasons they 4-S didn't get full marks). Okay, the other factors for just failing on 'Excellent' rating were as follows:* The Family Deal promises drinks and cookies for the children on arrival in the room - but they weren't there and we had to nudge the Front Desk to provide the items for which we were paying.* Another disappointment was at breakfast where the free re-fills of orange juice or smoothie that we had enjoyed during our last stay 3 years ago had stopped - $9 for a glass of juice IS a bit steep. You can breakfast easily enough in the Mandalay Bay Hotel restaurants - dining there is much cheaper too.* The ensuite bathrooms are beginning to show their age - plugs not working properly in the sink and fittings showing wear and tear, don't get me wrong, this is hair-splitting because they are still good but I stayed in the revamped Hilton Hotel in Sydney recently and its bathrooms are fantastic, they even have a plasma TV on the wall at the foot of the bath!On the plus side, the service at breakfast was very, very good and the beds, bedding and pillows are just the most comfortable you can find. Great job by the housekeeping staff - the room was immaculate every afternoon. The rooms are well equipped with good plasma TVs, chairs etc - but if you want milk with your coffee you have to bring your own for some reason.It's also a huge plus if you have children for them to make full use of the Mandalay Bay Hotel's beach and wave machine pool, the rapids too - and it was fantastic at very busy times there to be able to retreat to the Four Season's private pool and have free ice creams, mineral water spray and even cucumber slices for your jet-lagged eyelids (I kid you not).One other observation - if you are a family of five, use the monorail from Mandalay Bay to the Luxor of Excalibur for local transport, but after that use cabs as the general public monorail system is a ludicrous $5 per person and $25 gets a taxi to take you most of the places you want. We stayed three nights and it was a great way to get over the flight and we loved every minute. We would go back again but hope they don't penny pinch at breakfast any further and make plans to upgrade the bathrooms in good time.	
