Aug 3 2006 	Very nice experience at the FS	We stayed at the Four Seasons July 24-26. We booked the room as part of a SWA vacation package, and definitely got a great deal. Our reservations were for a Superior room, but the gracious front desk clerk upgraded us to a suite without us even asking for it. We arrived around 2:30pm, and were able to check in right away. However, we had to call the front desk when our luggage didn't arrive as promptly. Our suite was spacious, with a living area and extra bathroom, and the windows faced the airport, but we still had a view of the strip as well. The decor was pleasant and comfortable, the toiletries were L'Occitane (which we love), and our suite even had a portable humidifier, great for our dry eyes. We did notice the slow drainage in the sink, loud toilets, and small shower/tub, plus some wear and tear. I've never stayed in a FS before, and after reading the reviews on this website, I tried not to have very high expectations. Overall, though, we really liked this hotel and would definitely stay there again, but only if we get the same package deal. We thought the service was excellent, appreciated the quietness (we slept so soundly), and loved the pool and its amenities. Plus, it was nice having easy access to Mandalay Bay. Our pool experience was great -- we got fruit, popsicles, cold towels, Evian spritz, etc., and it didn't seem in dire need of cleaning. We noticed that the pool attendants were great with the kids there, and even saw one of the kids hug them good-bye! So, they're definitely family-friendly. The only other issue we had was with housekeeping, who forgot to replenish the sugar and cream. (But then, she also forgot to charge us for the 3 mini-bar drinks we had.) We also dined at Verandah, and I had one of the best omelettes ever! Parmesan french fries were very yummy as well. So, now that I've had the FS experience, I'm hooked!	
Jul 20 2006 	Not Worth It!!	After reading the glowing reviews here, we decided to give FSLV a try. We arrived at 2:00PM and our room wasn't ready. Neel, the fellow at the Front Desk, had a somewhat imperious attitude and I was made to feel as if I were to blame for arriving early. We were offered to wait at the Spa (huh?) or in the lobby, and they would call our cell phone when the room was ready. We decided to sit in the lobby and wait, hoping the room might be ready earlier than the 3:00 check-in. 3:00 came and still no phone call. Many other people who arrived after us were promptly shown to their rooms. Neel did not make eye contact with me the entire time we waited in the lobby, and disappeared around 3:00. At 3:10 I got up and asked about my room. Turns out it had been ready for 30 minutes! When I said that I was suppposed to have been called, they said that they had tried, but couldn't get through. No one bothered to walk across the lobby to tell me my room was ready. I wonder how long they would have let us sit there? This really started our vacation off on the wrong foot, and I was wondering where was the great FS service I had heard so much about? The didn't even offer an apology!We arrived on a Sunday, and during the reservation process I noted that we were celebrating our anniversary. During the check-in, I inquired about an upgrade, and was told &quot;we'll do our best&quot;, which apparently means no dice. We got our Moderate room with airport view, which is what we paid for so I can't complain....but an upgrade would have been nice.The room was OK. Compared to other rooms on the Strip (Venetian, Bellagio, Paris, Mirage, Alladin) I could have gotten a far better suite for what we paid for a very average room at FS. The plasma TV was nice, but it has an analog/mono feed, not High Def, not Stereo. This means the picture is stretched out over the big screen and the quality leaves a lot to be desired. The drain in the bathroom was incredibly slow. So slow that you couldn't leave the water running while you brushed your teeth. Also, the toilet flush was incredibly loud, and you could hear it when other guests would flush theirs, as their flush would often cause ours to gurgle. The outside air vent would not seal properly, which led to a constant whirring sound from air being let into the room. We got a newspaper day one, but not on day two.The pool could use a major cleaning. I had to ask for a cold face cloth. In the four hours we were at the pool, we were offered only one Evian spritz. We were not offered fruit, or cucumber slices as I read about here. On the positive side, the Verandah restaurant is very good and the service was excellent. The housekeeping service is also very good and cordial. For our anniversary, they sent up an &quot;amenity&quot; of a slice of cake. On the second night there, we were give a ride in the house car. All in all, we were not overly impressed. I've stayed at the FS in Maui and that is a far superior hotel and experience. FSLV has a lot of work to do to catch up. Our experience at their front desk was a disgrace to the FS brand.	
Jul 7 2006	Exactly What I've Come to Expect from the Four Seasons	My family (wife and 4 kids) and I spent a week around the 4th of July holiday at the Four Seasons primarily to visit relatives in the area, but also to explore areas around Las Vegas (Hoover Dam, Red Rock Canyon, etc.) and it did not disappoint. The Four Seasons Las Vegas met our high expectations of Four Seasons properties around the world and like other of their properties, they have recreated the wonderful rooms, facilities and location but really created an exceptional experience by their premium level of service accorded each guest.My expectations, in general tend to be high for Four Seasons properties and my wife and I tend to choose them regularly on our holidays because of our good experiences around the world. I was a bit apprehensive about this property in light of some of the reviews I had read about dogs on the property and my experience with Las Vegas hotels in general, but I am happy to say all of these concerns were overblown. The Four Seasons Hotel Las Vegas is in every way, deserving of the Four Seasons brand. More specifically, I'll break my review up into 3 sections:1. Room - Excellent - If you've stayed in a Four Seasons Room, this will be no different2. Location/Facilities - Excellent - On the Strip, but you'd never know if if you didn't want to3. Service - Excellent - Just like any other Four SeasonsROOM - The room is exactly what we have come to expect from the Four Seasons. Firm beds, the same Four Seasons sheets. If I was to be critical, the one issue we found was that the pillows (while nice) didn't seem to be the standard Four Seasons fare. The bathroom contained both a shower and a tub, thought the shower seemed a bit small (I bumped my elbows on occassion shampooing) though functional. If you've stayed in a Four Seasons room before, this room should offer no surprises.LOCATION/FACILITIES - As our primary purpose for our visit was to visit relatives and see sights outside of the city, the Four Seasons location was perfect. Located on the top floors (35-39) of the Mandalay Bay hotel, the hotel is located at the end of the Las Vegas Strip and accessible to the airport (a short drive) and the highway (right around the corner) without having to deal with the terrible traffic that plagues the Strip around rush hour and the evening. The pool, while simple, was an oasis. You'd never know that right over the wall is the gigantic Mandalay Bay wave pool (which Four Seasons guests have access to should they choose). Even over the 4th of July holiday, we had no problems getting lounge chairs, etc. In the evening, when they close the pools (7 pm) there is a nice private walking path open to hotel guests (of the Four Seasons and Mandalay bay) only which we walked with our kids on in the late evening to get them over their jetlag. A great alternative than having them wander the Strip or in a casino. We did pop over to the Mandalay Bay a couple times during our stay to go to restaurants and a casino. The Four Seasons has several access points into the Mandalay Bay including a private access for Four Seasons guests directly into the Mandalay Bay lobby from the Four Seasons guest elevators. So there's no need to worry that you'll need ot take a cab or a long walk to the casino if that's what you'd like to do. There are a couple of restaurants on property, but we only ate at Verandah, essentially their coffee shop next to the pool. Food was fine, though the service staff and kitchen seemed a bit stretched when full during the 4th of July holiday. As a result, our breakfasts on that day took about 30-40 minutes to come out. The manager handled it nicely, though, offering a plate of freshly sliced fruit for the family until our food arrived.SERVICE - End to End service was exceptional, even for a Four Seasons, in my view. When we arrived, we were brought to our room by a guest services who noted when we wanted our rooms to be made up each day and when we preferred turn down service (and indeed, service was provided on the dot!). In addition, with 4 children, the provided milk and cookies each night and, on the day we arrived, spelled each of our children's names in colorful sponges on the bathtub which made bath time that much easier for our smaller children. If there was one criticism, like the restaurant, the valet service seemed a bit overwhelmed during the 4th of July weekend. In summary, on all aspects, the Four Seasons met our high expectations of Four Seasons properties around the world and like other of their properties, they have recreated the wonderful rooms, facilities and location but really created an exceptional experience by their premium level of service accorded each guest.	
