Aug 27 2004	Avoid the crowds and leave pampered!	This was my first time in Vegas and my fiance's second time in about 8 years. Before arriving here, I checked the reviews on this site and many others before booking. We were so happy with our stay, we couldn't wait to come back and share our thoughts on this site! We did pay about $250/night with the $25 credit/day, but comparable hotels like the Bellagio and Mandalay Bay have the same rates, and are extremely crowded EVERYWHERE and just too blatantly fancy. The Four Seasons is a hotel for people who don't need a lot of obvious glitz and glamour to feel like you're getting what you paid for. The room was very clean and tastefully decorated with original artwork and quality bath products from L'occitane each day. The rooms are tended to twice a day and newspapers are delivered daily in the morning. Room service was also convenient and tasted great. We didn't use the spa, but took advantage of the gym and pool almost every day. There are tropical flowers and baskets of apples and oranges. The gym is clean and had mint condition machinery. Gatorade and lemon water, headsets, TVs on each machine, magazines, anything you need-- you have. The locker room is like a spa in itself. Steam room, robes, lockers, towels, slippers, shavers, great soap, shampoo, toner, lotion cotton balls, Q-Tips.. The concierge at FS was very helpful and friendly and helped us book tickets to O, Blue Man Group and George Wallace. All will keep you captivated for the entire time. We only had one bad experience with a restaurant, Fusia, when we paid for a package with Blue Man Group. Food was too sweet and the prefix meal was definitely not worth it. We loved our waitress though, who was very friendly and gave us a complimentary dessert at the end. On the last day, Monday, we headed to the Mandalay Bay area for breakfast and found all the restaurants had long lines! Even Raffles, which wasn't very good always had a long line (but they are open late in the night). So... we headed back to the FS and ate breakfast there for the third time. No lines, beautiful palm tree views, sounds of water from the pool nearby, amazing service and food. That day we actually ate AT the Verandah itself, since it was opening day. Previously breakfast was served next door at Charlie Palmer Steak until the Verandah's renovations were completed. We were also there for Verandah's opening night dinner, which offered a free entree with one full entree. The new restaurant is gorgeous, with beautiful woodwork, lighting, outdoor seating. There are even loveseats for couples who want to sit next to each other. The food was delicious and our waiter was very friendly and gave us some great information about the renovation process.Even the people who stay at the FS are friendly. Visitors in the elevators say &quot;hello&quot; and ask how your trip is doing when you run into each other again. At THE hotel, it seemed more like a place to be seen. Some visitors and staff were very obnoxious when giving directions or passing you in the crowds at the lobby. The Bellagio, Paris and others were beautiful, but again there were crowds everywhere and just generally not easy to get around. It was great to be able to visit all the other hotels, but even better to be able to come back to the Four Seasons and feel you have left the chaos behind you. PS: Don't forget to read the awards FS has won in Vegas and around the world on Forbes! Tip from my sister, another trip planner!	
Aug 16 2004	Beyond the call	Given all of the other reviews, mine seems redundant. But this is an extraordinary property --all the more so because it is in Las Vegas. Were it in any other city, it would be a first rate hotel but might not seem quite so remarkable. But it is an oasis of grace in a city where that quality is not always evident. The service was extraordinary. A sign of this is the following: The Verandah, the casual dining restaurant, was closed for renovation during my mid-August stay. The space I gather had been used as an alternative was booked for a wedding. Another hotel might simply have said, &quot;Too bad! There is no scarcity of dining spots in Vegas. Go to Mandalay Bay. Or call room service.&quot; The Four Seasons instead set up a small meeting room with a buffet, a full bar, a huge wine selection, etc., etc. I doubt they had more than a couple of dozen guests for dinner that evening. (And given the small room, etc., they clearly did not expect many more.) There seemed to be nearly that many servers, bartenders, etc. To have gone to this trouble is a sign of the way the FS works. Who could grumble if the warm food at the buffet was at time only luke warm? It was the thought that counted.	
Aug 15 2004	Not Worth the Price	I booked a standard room (mountain view) for two nights (August 10-11) at a cost of $250 per night. As part of the &quot;Oasis Package&quot; this included a $25 credit per day towards incidentals. The appearance of the hotel is nice, but underwhelming based on its 5-star AAA rating. Most of the Fairmont Hotels I have stayed at are superior. The room amenities were good (top quality sheets, furnishings, etc.) and the room was a modest size - a few glitches like a slow drain, but maid service was very good. All of the staff were friendly and helpful. I think it simply doesn't compare to the finer hotels of the world. I could have stayed at Bellagio for a lower rate ($199-$239). The Bellagio was crawling with people when I visited and I think presents a different type of option (less serene though more luxurious overall). I am not sure if the cost of the room that you stay in at the Four Seasons is directly relative to the enjoyment of your stay, but I expect it is. Service at the small pool area was good, but had to wait for ice water refills the first day, and others did not automatically get ice water. This was tough in 112F weather. It is great to have separate elevators from Mandalay Bay to get to your room quickly, and still have full use of the facilities at Mandalay. Mandalay was busy, and all the pool areas were packed with people, and lots of kids. Nice to have the option of a quieter pool area at Four Seasons. Had to show photo ID with room key and card holder to eat at the Mandalay Buffet and charge the expense to my room. I found this very annoying. The on-site car rental cost $59/day for an intermediate vehicle (only one available). I felt ripped off as web rates would put the rental closer to $35.99/day. In terms of value for money, I think a $200 per night rate or less would be more reasonable (or slightly more for a strip view) and cannot imagine paying over $250 during the high season. Another negative is the location, if you do intend to move up and down the strip. You can catch a monorail to Luxor/Excalibur but the hotter resorts are mid-strip. I stayed at Ballys for $69 dollars per night in a renovated room. That was full value for money, though again, an entirely different experience. I would recommend staying in two different hotels to experience the differences.	
Jul 27 2004	loved the four seasons	We just returned from 4 seasons las vegas. we stayed there july 22-july 25 2004. when we arrived the power was out in the entire hotel. the hotel was operating on generators and all of the shops, restaurants and pools were closed. We were greeted at the desk by Gregg Cummings. He immediately upgraded us to a strip view room. We were greeted with four chocolate covered strawberried. The service was impeccable. Our room was gorgeous and we were able lie in bed and look down the strip. It was fabulous. I cannot impress how wonderful it is to have access to the Mandalay property but also be able to escape to an oasis of calm smoke free sopistication. As a 4 seasons guest we were able to enjoy the best of both worlds in Las Vegas.I can say that the chaos of the Mandalay Bay pool was similar to being at a busy day at raging waters. There were too many people, too many wild kids and no servers or waitresses. We lasted at the Mandalay pool for 10 minutes.We went straight back to the 4 seasons. We were greeted by steve who set up our lounge chairs, got our pitcher of water, and misted us as we relaxed poolside while listening to classical music.We had massages at the 4 seasons spa. Clay was my massuse. It was the best deep tissue massage I have ever had. The serenity of the spa and it's treatment rooms was wonderful.The service, the food, and the atmosphere make this a wonderful getaway. We will definetly go back to Vegas and from this point forward we will only stay at the 4 seasons.	
Jul 26 2004	Too bad there was a power outage	My husband and I stayed here from the 21st - 24th of July. It was a lovely hotel, quiet and calm compared to the Mandalay Bay. Unfortunately, there was a power outage on our second day, which meant no pools! Even the Mandalay Bay pools were closed which was a real inconvenience at it was 110 degrees. All in all we had a great stay, even though we didn't experience any of the &quot;personal touches&quot; other reviewers mention.	
Jul 21 2004	The best as always!	We originally were not scheduled to be at the Four Seasons as they were sold out, but as fate had it, we were desitined to stay there. We had just checked in to The Hotel which is part of Mandalay Bay. From the minute we got out of the cab, we just seemed to run into one thing after another. First no bellman in sight to help with luggage, long waits at the front desk while we waited for 20 minutes while someone under-age with no ID was trying to explain why he should get a room key to a room he was sharing with 5 others and finally after leaving the beautiful room we had been assigned, we came back an hour later to find that they were right in the middle of shampooing the carpets in our room. Consequently, we were told we could have a lesser room. At that point is when the Four Seasons magic began.We called and pleaded with the Front Desk at the Four Seasons and told them of our plight. At that time a room did come available, it was a Las Vegas Suite which was offered to us for 1/2 the rack rate. The front desk manager personally came to The Hotel along with an associate to meet us and carried our luggage through the Mandalay Bay and checked us into our beautiful suite. I was so impressed by this personal service which is their trademark.Once ensconced, the room was just gorgeous which was shortly followed by a lovely welcoming amenity to add to our joy. The view, the amenities and the service were just perfect. We spend some time wandering around the hotel and couldn't help but notice what a civilized oasis it was from the hectic hustle and bustle of the other hotels and from the smoke and noise. It was always such a relief to come back after being out.It was very expensive but definitely worth the price because you definitely get what you pay for.	
Jul 12 2004	nothing's perfect but	four seasons comes as close to a perfect vacation as you can get. If you want to just get away from it all and be luxuriously pampered, this is the place. Yes, the room rate is high, but being treated to the amentities in the spa or sitting poolside while an attendant brings you lemon water, orange slices and sprays you with Evian mist, priceless. Four seasons delivers and then some.	
Jul 12 2004	The Best Hotel In Las Vegas	This is the letter that I wrote to the GM of the hotelDear Four Seasons,I would like to begin this letter on point, before going into full detail about our stay. You should be proud to know that we feel that you run &quot;the&quot; best hotel in the city of Las Vegas. We have been to Vegas five times, and out hotels have included The Bellagio, MGM Grand, and Venetian. Everything from the lobby to the pool rivals that of those hotels stated. We were greeted with a beautiful room that was ready upon our arrival, as per a request for early check-in. And enjoyed a wonderful lunch by the pool, during our stay our servers included Katie, Chaz and Leslie. Leslie was wonderful, she treated our family with such care and love, and should certainly be looked upon as the best of your staff. Everyone at the pool was magnificent, we were given such personal attention, towards the end of our stay we were even greeted by name, before even checking in. Pool attendants included Steve, Margaret, Vivian, James and Moses. And at the porte cochere Gerry the valet was wonderful, always greeting us with a pleasant smile every evening. Those however are just a handful of names that we remember, but we cannot say that we had a single less then standard attendant, they were all magnificent. On the last day of our stay, after checking out, our daughter Ashli became very ill, almost immediately James, Leslie, and Moses, were on the phone with the front desk, and within minutes we had a room for a few hours so she could rest away from the blazing heat. This is service that goes above and beyond what anyone else would do, and truly sets the Four Seasons apart from all others. Every single inch of the hotel exudes a level of service is bar none of anything we have ever experienced. I was truly amazed. Although nothing is perfect, the Four Seasons is close, and to help you get there I would like to offer you some suggestion. Compared to the other hotels in Las Vegas, your housekeeping, or turndown service is extremely below standard. Robes and slippers should be placed near the bed, and something should be offered such as bottled water fruit or chocolate. With the exception of that area, please keep up the excellent work. We have spoken about next years trip, and even with all of the new hotels opening, the Four Seasons Las Vegas will be the only hotel that the we will stay at forever more.	
Jul 8 2004	Amazing Service	Stayed here for our anniversary a few weeks ago, had the best time we have ever had at any hotel. Amazing service, great restaurants, great time...	
Jul 8 2004	Best Hotel of my life - hands down!	We just got back yesterday from a 4 night stay at the Four Seasons Las Vegas (July 2 - July 6 2004). To summarize - we have a one year old and 3 year old so it is really important that when we get the opportunity to get away it is perfect. I can honestly say (and my husband and I are very critical) that I wouldn't change a thing. We cashed in all of our mileage points so we could afford paying $ 120 a night for the room and it was worth it. We had one issue where a dog in the neighboring room was barking while we were trying to take a nap. We called down and they moved us to a beautiful suite. The Four Seasons staff were spectacular some examples: leaving us chocolate as an apology for the dog issue, filling the ice bucket in our room, fabulous L'Occitane soap, shampoo and lotion, house car that can take you for free within 3 miles of the hotel if you ask, they printed our Southwest boarding passes via the internet at midnight so we could get preferred seating... We went to the pool and they escort you to a chair of your choice and prepare the chair with a fitting towel, bring you a big pitcher of ice water with lemon and offer drinks or food. It was fabulous - we are not accustomed to this so we felt a bit out of our league but that was fine with us! I had wondered if these reviews were for real - our is for real. If you are thinking of staying at a really nice place you will not be disappointed at the Four Seasons - promise!	
Jul 7 2004	As good as it gets	To get a hotel any better than this you will have to die.....and go to heaven.Stayed here over 4th of July weekend and was blown away. The service, food, and decor are not of this world.The pool/spa/healthclub are spectacular. Prepare to be spoiled with small touches (each treadmill has its own TV attached to it, the pool attendants will bring fruit and evian to you on a regular basis, the bath tubs are extremely deep, dry cleaning and laundry comes back in an hour, the beds are soft and plush, and the list goes on and on). The price is as high as it gets in Las Vegas, but is very reasonable by the standards of other cities. A hotel like this in Paris or New York would be at least three times the price. MUST STAY HERE TO BELIEVE HOW GOOD IT IS.	
