Jun 29 2004	A value proposition? Absolutely!	Sure there are less expensive alternatives in the super luxe category, and all of them come with casinos and the many trappings of a big LV resort...but if you really want to get away from reality in the neon land of unreality, then the Four Seasons Las Vegas is your best bet. Spent the better part of 100 degree days poolside getting spritzed by aerosolized Evian, treated to wedges of fresh oranges, cooled by rolled chilled wet towlettes, satiated by bottomless pitchers of lemon water, waited on hand and foot by attentive and attractive human life forms, poolside menu by Charlie Palmer (the lobster roll!), afternoon hot stone massages worked the lunch off, leaving room for Charlie Palmer's Steakhouse for dinner, and immediate access to all of the pleasures of Mandalay Bay. PERFECTION. PRICELESS.	
May 20 2004	Unbelievable level of service	We were lucky enough to stay at the Four Seasons for a friend's wedding. We loved how you could be in the frenetic activity of the Mandalay Bay one minute, and then walk through the doors of the Four Seasons &amp; be enveloped in quiet luxury the next. Although Four Seasons guests can use all the amenities of the Mandalay as well, the difference between the two was quite marked. Although the Mandalay had a fun &quot;wave pool&quot; and a &quot;lazy river&quot;, we quickly tired of the lack of umbrellas under the hot sun, the crowded &quot;beach&quot;, and the lack of privacy. We scooted back over to the Four Seasons side, and while the pool itself was nothing special, the individual cabanas (no charge) with overhead water spritzers, telephones, and food &amp; drink service was the height of luxury. Having a Cobb Salad &amp; diet coke delivered to enjoy while I relaxed under my cabana was the best! But the greatest indicator of the level of service was when my husband forgot his cumberbund. While the Mandaley offered no help, the concierge at the Four Seasons said, &quot;just a moment&quot;, turned around, and came back with a loaner cumberbund. Unbelievable!	
May 13 2004	Many Problems over Multiple Stays but Still a Good Hotel	We've stayed at the Four Seasons Las Vegas nearly 6 times, and are scheduled to be there again in late June. Overall, it's the finest hotel in LV, but over years we've certainly had problems. Even though we had a confirmed reservation and were return customers, they were overbooked when we arrived to check in. They put us up in a suite @ the Mandalay Bay overnight. It was disgustingly filthy. Large stains in the carpeting, on the sofa, and the soap holders in the bath were broken off and laying on the vanity. Another time as we were departing, I was stuggling with loading my luggage into our rental car at the porte cochere. The main valet/bellman viewed the situation, and kept talking with a co-worker no more than 10 feet from me. I shot him a disapproving look, but perhaps because I am Asian, he did not feel the need to offer his assistance. I've never forgotten how I departed after staying there for a full week, in a strip-view suite.Yet on another stay at the Four Seasons, the bellman had lost my leather jacket. We'd arrived before our room was ready, so the bellman took our luggage and coats, while we had lunch. He put our luggage into our room when it was finally ready, but not my jacket. Apparently, he'd hung it in another guest's closet - he couldn't remember which room, as there had been many arrivals that particular day.I'm only going back this June because of the hotel's sense of quiet and privacy.	
